    <div class="prose sqs-html-content">
      <h2>Work and Interests</h2>
      <p>
        My work has centered on interaction design and usability in a variety of domains,
        including Human-Computer Interaction, Product Design, Digital Art, and Learning. I am
        a <a href="https://www.hcde.washington.edu/craft"><strong>Teaching Professor</strong></a> in
        the Department of
        <a href="https://www.hcde.washington.edu/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"
          ><strong>Human Centered Design &amp; Engineering</strong></a
        >
        at the University of Washington and director of our BS program.
      </p>
      <p>
        Previously, I was a <strong>Lecturer</strong> in
        <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physical_computing" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"
          >Physical Computing</a
        >
        at
        <a href="https://www.gold.ac.uk/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Goldsmiths, University of London</a>
        in the Department of Computing and served as <strong>Senior Tutor</strong> on the MA in Information
        Experience Design at the
        <a href="https://www.rca.ac.uk/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Royal College of Art</a>. As a
        <strong>Research Fellow</strong> at the London Knowledge Lab, I focused on
        <a href="http://www.ld-grid.org/">Learning Design</a>,
        <a href="http://ldse.org.uk/">tools for pedagogy design</a>, technology-enhanced learning (TEL), and
        interactive artefacts. My prior research was on using traditional design methods such as sketching to
        support software engineering for information visualisation. My areas of specialist knowledge are
        Information Visualization, Human-Computer Interaction, Physical Computing, and Learning Design.
      </p>

      <h2>Background</h2>
      <p>
        I was a Partner at design firm <a href="https://www.tinkerlondon.com/">TinkerLondon</a>, where we worked on
        projects that bridged the digital and physical worlds with interactive technology. I’ve worked as a
        <strong>consultant</strong> on a range of projects in both User Experience and Information Design/Analysis. See
        <a href="https://www.brockcraft.com/teaching-publications">Teaching and Publications</a> for a list of clients
        and projects.
      </p>
      <p>
        In 2007, I completed PhD research at UCL Interaction Centre (<a
          href="https://uclic.ucl.ac.uk/"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer">UCLIC</a
        >) in the area of Information Visualization Design methodology. My design method is called
        <a href="https://www.brockcraft.com/visualization-design">SoViz</a> and is aimed at supporting software
        visualization design through collaboration and sketching. For a .pdf version, or if you are interested in
        visualization design, please contact me. I received awards from the UCL Graduate School Research Images as
        Art competition for images that were produced in the course of my research. Here are the winning images from
        <a
          href="https://www.grad.ucl.ac.uk/comp/2005-2006/research/gallery/index.pht?entryID=056"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer">2006</a
        >
        and
        <a
          href="https://www.grad.ucl.ac.uk/comp/2006-2007/research/gallery/index.pht?entryID=163"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer">2007</a
        >. These were produced with software called Context Free and Processing.
      </p>
      <p>
        In the distant past, I was a member of the post-punk studio band, the
        <a href="https://www.discogs.com/artist/788651-The-Christal-Methodists" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"
          >Christal Methodists</a
        >, which produced culture-jamming electronic music that was almost unlistenable.
      </p>
      <p>
        <a href="https://twitter.com/thatbrock" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">@thatbrock</a><br />
        thatbrock[@]gmail.com
      </p>
